DML (Data Manipulation Language) 
--------------------------------
-These commands are given to store/ update/ delete data. 
Example: 
        1.INSERT 
        2.UPDATE 
        3.DELETE 

CRUD
----
1.Create
------
-This operation is about creating or adding new records to the table.
-Create data with INSERT command

Table: User 
Columns: (id, name, age) 

Example:
        CREATE TABLE user(
        	id int,
            name varchar(30),
            age int
        );
        DESC user;

        | [Field] | [Type]        | [Null] | [Key] | [Default] | [Extra] |
        |  id     | int           |  YES   |       |   NULL    |         |
        |  name   | varchar(30)   |  YES   |       |   NULL    |         |
        |  age    | int           |  YES   |       |   NULL    |         |
Adding Data in to Table
-----------------------
-INSERT command is used to add data into the table.

Case1: (Insert Data to All Columns) 
Syntax: 
      INSERT INTO <table_name> VALUES(value1,value2....valuen); 
      INSERT INTO <table_name>(col1_name, col2_name â€¦) VALUES(value1,value2....valuen); 
Exaple:
      INSERT INTO user values(1,'Akash',22);
      SELECT * FROM user;

      | [id] | [name]  | [age] |
      |  1   | Akash   |  22   |

Case2: (Insert Partial Data) 
Syntax:
      INSERT INTO <table_name>(colname1,colname2,..) VALUES (value1,value2...) 
Example: 
      INSERT INTO user(id,name,age) VALUES (2,'Anshu',21);
      SELECT * FROM user;

      | [id] | [name]  | [age] |
      |  1   | Akash   |  22   |
      |  2   | Anshu   |  21   |

Case3: (Insert Multiple Rows) 
Syntax: 
      INSERT INTO <table_name> values(value1,value2..),(value1,value2..),(valuen,valuen..); 
Example:
        INSERT INTO user values	(3,'Ashu',22),
						(4,'Abhi',22),
						(5,'Biswa',20);

        SELECT * FROM user;

      | [id] | [name]  | [age] |
      |  1   | Akash   |  22   |
      |  2   | Anshu   |  21   |
      |  3   | Ashu    |  22   |
      |  4   | Abhi    |  22   |
      |  5   | Biswa   |  20   |

Case4: (Insert NULL values)
Example:
        INSERT INTO user values	(6,'Ashu',NULL)
        SELECT * FROM user;

        | [id] | [name]  | [age] |
        |  1   | Akash   |  22   |
        |  2   | Anshu   |  21   |
        |  3   | Ashu    |  22   |
        |  4   | Abhi    |  22   |
        |  5   | Biswa   |  20   |
        |  6   | Ashu    |  NULL |

2.UPDATE( Modify/Update Data )
--------
-UPDATE command is used to update data of a table.
Case1: (Modify Single Column)
Syntax:
      UPDATE <table_name> SET col1=value WHERE condition;  
Example:
      UPDATE user set name='Ghadai' where id=1;
      SELECT * FROM user;

      | [id] | [name]  | [age] |
      |  1   | Ghadai  |  22   |
      |  2   | Anshu   |  21   |
      |  3   | Ashu    |  22   |
      |  4   | Abhi    |  22   |
      |  5   | Biswa   |  20   |
      |  6   | Ashu    |  NULL |

Case2: (Modify Multiple Column)
Syntax:
      UPDATE <table_name> SET col1=value,col2=value WHERE condition; 
Example:
      UPDATE user set name='Akash',age=23 where id=2;
      SELECT * FROM user;

      | [id] | [name]  | [age] |
      |  1   | Ghadai  |  22   |
      |  2   | Akash   |  23   |
      |  3   | Ashu    |  22   |
      |  4   | Abhi    |  22   |
      |  5   | Biswa   |  20   |
      |  6   | Ashu    |  NULL |

Case4- (Update All Rows)
Example:
        UPDATE user set age=30;
        SELECT * FROM user;

        | id | name   | age |
        | 1  | Ghadai | 30  |
        | 2  | Akash  | 30  |
        | 3  | Ashu   | 30  |
        | 4  | Abhi   | 30  |
        | 5  | Biswa  | 30  |
        | 6  | Ashu   | 30  |

3.Delete Data 
-------------
-DELETE command is used to delete data from a table.

Case1: (Delete Specific Rows)
Syntax:
      DELETE FROM <table_name> WHERE condition;
Example:
      DELETE FROM user where id=6;
      SELECT * FROM user;

      | id | name   | age |
      | 1  | Ghadai | 30  |
      | 2  | Akash  | 30  |
      | 3  | Ashu   | 30  |
      | 4  | Abhi   | 30  |
      | 5  | Biswa  | 30  |
 
Case2: (Delete All Rows)
Syntax:
      DELETE FROM <table_name>;
Example:
      DELETE FROM user;
      SELECT * FROM user;

      | id | name   | age |

Retrieve Data(SELECT)
---------------------
-SELECT command is used to retrieve data from the table.
Appraoch1: (All Rows + All Columns)
Syntax: 
      SELECT * FROM <table_name>; 
      SELECT colname1,colname2,colname3 FROM <table_name>; 
Example:
        SELECT * FROM user;
        SELECT id,name,age FROM user;

        | id | name  | age |
        | 1  | Ghadai| 30  |
        | 2  | Akash | 30  |
        | 3  | Ashu  | 30  |
        | 4  | Abhi  | 30  |
        | 5  | Biswa | 30  |

Appraoch2: (All Rows + Specific Column)  
Syntax:
      SELECT colname1 FROM <table_name>; 
Example:
      SELECT id,name from user;

      | id | name   |
      | 1  | Ghadai |
      | 2  | Akash  |
      | 3  | Ashu   |
      | 4  | Abhi   |
      | 5  | Biswa  |

Appraoch3: (Specific Rows + All Columns) 
Syntax:
      SELECT * FROM <table_name> WHERE condition; 
Example:
      SELECT * FROM user where id=2;

      | id | name  | age |
      | 2  | Akash | 30  |

Appraoch4: (Specific Rows + Specific Columns)
Syntax:
      SELECT colname1, colname2 FROM <table_name> WHERE condition; 
Example:
      SELECT id,name FROM user WHERE id=1;
  
      | id | name   |
      | 1  | Ghadai |












































